text: A Mobile App for Police to Track Car Status Summary of Final Year Project

The objective of our final year project is the design and development of a mobile application, "PolicePlus," dedicated to police forces for tracking and managing the status of vehicles. This project aims to address challenges such as rapid verification of vehicle information, realtime detection of infractions (e.g., stolen status, expired documents), and optimization of law enforcement interventions. The application enables officers to scan license plates or manually query vehicle data, instantly accessing registered information, reporting anomalies, and facilitating administrative document verification via an intuitive interface. Key technologies employed include Kotlin with Jetpack Compose for the Android application, Node.js with Express for the backend API, MySQL for the database, and UML for system modeling. The system integrates with external data sources like insurance databases and leverages tools like Retrofit, Dagger Hilt, Figma, Git, and cloud deployment platforms (Render, Clever Cloud). This summary outlines the projectâ€™s context, design methodology, implementation details, and key features.
Keywords: Mobile Application, Police, Vehicle Management, Car Status Tracker, License Plate Recognition, UML, Kotlin, Jetpack Compose, Node.js, Express, MySQL, API, Android.

Today, the world is witnessing significant technological advancements in all sectors, particularly in road safety and vehicle tracking. Modern technologies now enable law enforcement agencies to use mobile applications to monitor and manage vehicle status in real time. Police officers often face numerous challenges, such as quickly identifying vehicles, verifying documents, and detecting infractions. Thanks to computing and web services, it is now possible to enhance the efficiency of these operations by automating the process of vehicle control and tracking. In this context, we have been led to design, develop, and implement a mobile application dedicated to vehicle management by the police. This application aims to centralize information, provide instant access to vehicle data, and facilitate officersâ€™ interventions in the field. Our application is designed to improve vehicle management and optimize law enforcement operations to enhance the reliability of inspections, reduce response times, and minimize human errors. This chapter provides a general overview of the work context and the objectives of our final year project. We will begin by outlining some of the challenges faced by law enforcement and the importance of an information system for police operations.
Importance of Police Role and Security Measures

The police play a crucial role in ensuring road and vehicle safety by implementing security measures to reduce violations related to vehicle conditions. Ensuring that vehicles are roadworthy is essential to prevent accidents caused by mechanical failures or the deterioration of critical components. The police conduct regular inspection campaigns to detect vehicles that do not meet legal standards, such as those with faulty brakes, lighting, or tires, which may pose risks to drivers and pedestrians. They also impose fines and penalties on violators to ensure compliance with laws designed to enhance road safety. In addition, the police contribute to raising awareness among drivers about the importance of regular vehicle maintenance through educational and awareness programs. They also utilize modern technologies, such as smart cameras and electronic inspection devices, to monitor vehicle conditions and effectively detect violations. Thus, the role of the police in enforcing security measures is not limited to imposing laws but also includes promoting a culture of road safety awareness, which helps reduce accident rates and ensures a safer traffic environment for everyone.

Unified Modeling Language (UML) is a standardized modeling language used to visualize the design of a system. It provides a set of diagrams to represent the structure and behavior of a system, making it easier to communicate ideas and designs among stakeholders. UML diagrams are used in the object-oriented design process to outline the system architecture, interactions, and flows.
Use Case Diagram: Shows the interactions between users (actors) and the system,
Class Diagram: Describes the structure of the system by showing the systemâ€™s classes,
Sequence Diagram: Represents the interactions between objects in a sequential order.
Activity Diagram: Depicts the flow of control or data through the system.
In the context of the police officerâ€™s app for vehicle tracking and violations, the main actors are as follows:

Police Officer: The primary user of the system. Police officers can register or log in, scan license plates to identify vehicles, view vehicle status (insurance, stolen status, etc.), file tickets for violations, and report stolen cars.

Traffic Management: Manages and populates the database with car, officer, and violation records. They ensure the system has up-to-date data for the police officers to use during their interactions with the app.

Car Owner (Implicit): While the car owner is not directly interacting with the system, they are an essential data subject. The car owner can report a stolen car through a separate interface or be impacted when a car is flagged as stolen by the police.

The system is designed to facilitate the tracking of vehicles by police officers, utilizing modern mobile and backend technologies. The implementation focuses on providing a seamless user experience with a well-structured backend to handle vehicle data, along with efficient tools for managing and storing this information.
The development of the application involved a combination of tools and technologies that ensured efficient coding practices, scalability, and high performance.
Mobile App: Kotlin, Jetpack Compose, Android Studio, Room (local DB), Dagger Hilt

The application is designed to simplify the process of tracking vehicles for police officers, providing easy access to critical vehicle data such as insurance details, stolen status, and ticket information. The following section summarizes the user flow and highlights the key interfaces that make up the app.

The primary goal of the application is to allow a police officer to quickly search for vehicle information using a license plate number. After logging into the app, the officer can initiate a license plate scan or enter a plate number manually. The system fetches relevant data such as
ownership, insurance status, and any tickets associated with the vehicle. In addition to the scan and search features, the officer can view their profile and access a history of scanned vehicles.

This project focuses on tracking vehicle statuses and assisting police officers in verifying vehiclerelated information. We have developed an application that enables law enforcement to efficiently access and manage vehicle data in real time. The application allows police officers to check essential vehicle documents, including the registration certificate, driverâ€™s license, insurance details, technical inspection status, and tax receipts. It also facilitates quick identification of anomalies, such as stolen vehicles or expired documents. Additionally, officers can receive alerts and take immediate action when necessary. For the development of our application, we used Android Studio, Adobe Figma, and MySQL. We also plan to enhance the system with offline functionality and more security measures to improve efficiency and reliability.
